Radiology CYOA Analysis

Ramie Fathy

October 21, 2019

R Markdown

Read in Data, change column names:

preceptorData <- read.csv("Pulmonary Course Preceptor Survey (Responses) - Form Responses 1.csv", header = TRUE)
colnames(preceptorData) <- c("Timestamp", "CYOA", "FormatSatisfaction", 
                             "StudentPreparation", "SessionDifficulty", 
                             "BestTeachingMethod", "FacilitatorUtility", 
                             "StudentEngagement", "PreceptorParticipation",
                             "StudentPace", "QuestionQuality", "CaseDiscussion",
                             "ImageInterpretation", "ExpectationClarity",
                             "PreceptorPreparation", "SelfDirectedLearning",
                             "ClinicalDecisionMaking", "Liked", "WouldChange")
studentCYOAData <- read.xlsx("Pulm Rad survey responses-2.xlsx", sheetIndex = 1)
studentCYOAData <- studentCYOAData %>% mutate(smallGroupType = "CYOA")
studentLinearData <- read.xlsx("Pulm Rad survey responses-2.xlsx", sheetIndex = 2)
studentLinearData <- studentLinearData  %>% mutate(smallGroupType = "Linear")
studentData <- rbind(studentCYOAData, studentLinearData)
colnames(studentData) <- c("Engaged", "Difficulty", "Satisfied", "Radiology",
                           "Linear", "SelfDirected", "Decisions", 
                           "ClinicalDecisionMaking", "Pace", "ChestImagingTest",
                           "RadiologyElective", "Facilitator", 
                           "LearningEnvironment", "EducationalMethod", "Liked",
                           "ToChange", "Q1", "Q2", "Q3", "Q4", "TotalCorrect",
                           "PercentCorrect", "totalWithoutOne", 
                           "percentWithoutOne", "SmallGroupType")
#exclude incomplete cases
studentData <- studentData[complete.cases(studentData),]

Students in CYOA Small Groups were more engaged and satisfied with the experience, and they did appreciate the pace more, though they did find the small group to be more difficult.

Facilitators were more highly rated in the Linear Small Group cohort.

There was no difference in the percent correct on the quiz between the two groups.

# Distribution of Performances on Quiz by Small Group Type

#exclude surveys where students selected multiple Preferred Educational Methods
studentDataLim <- studentData  %>% filter(EducationalMethod %in% 
                                       c("a", "b", "c", "d", "e", "f", "g")) %>%
  mutate(EducationalMethodType = fct_recode(EducationalMethod, 
                                            "Traditional Lecture" = "a",
                                            "Worksheet" = "b",
                                            "CYOA" = "c",
                                            "Textbook" = "d",
                                            "Self Study" = "e",
                                            "Video" = "f",
                                            "One on One Tutorial" = "g"))
# make a histogram of Preferred Educational Method - CYOA wins out in both

No difference in Radiology, Linear, or Radiology Elective, but all other comparisons were different when using a t-test to compare the average Likert Scale values (where Strongly Disagree = 1 and Strongly Agree = 5).

Mann-Whitney U-tests to Compare Distributions

wilcox.test((studentData %>% filter(SmallGroupType == "CYOA"))$Engaged, 
            (studentData %>% filter(SmallGroupType == "Linear"))$Engaged)

    Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction

data:  (studentData %>% filter(SmallGroupType == "CYOA"))$Engaged and (studentData %>% filter(SmallGroupType == "Linear"))$Engaged
W = 2981.5, p-value = 9.072e-08
alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
wilcox.test((studentData %>% filter(SmallGroupType == "CYOA"))$Difficulty,
